{"view":"article","slug":"6x6-l2c","category":"Big","subcategory":null,"topDir":"Big","title":{"en":"6x6 L2C Algorithms (Last Two Centers)"},"content":{"en":"<p><strong>6x6 L2C Algorithms (Last Two Centers)</strong></p><p>xyzzy</p><p><a href=\"http://www.speedsolving.com/forum/threads/6x6x6-l2c-one-look-last-bar-algorithms.66292/#post-1254063\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">http://www.speedsolving.com/forum/threads/6x6x6-l2c-one-look-last-bar-algorithms.66292/#post-1254063</a></p><p><u>http://www.speedsolving.com/forum/threads/a-collection-of-algorithms.708/page-98#post-1227435</u></p><p>The algorithms provide some good ideas and techniques that we could learn. Commutator (or cancelling with commutator).Generally, 6x6 L2C method is:    </p><div class=\"table-wrap\"><table><tbody><tr><td><p><img src=\"/stats/tutorial/media/6x6-l2c/en/image2.svg\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></p></td><td><p><img src=\"/stats/tutorial/media/6x6-l2c/en/image4.svg\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2×4 block</p></td><td><p>3×4 block</p></td></tr><tr><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td><p><img src=\"/stats/tutorial/media/6x6-l2c/en/image6.svg\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></p></td><td><p><img src=\"/stats/tutorial/media/6x6-l2c/en/image8.svg\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Use one oblique and two outer X-centers to form a partial bar and insert</p></td><td><p>Use a commutator dealing with a stray oblique</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>Apart from step 4, this is mostly done intuitively. Just like <a href=\"/tutorial/f2l\" class=\"see-also-link\" data-see-also=\"true\">F2L</a>, however, it doesn't hurt to look at a more algorithmic approach; here, we focus on using algorithms to combine steps 3 and 4 above.</p><p>There are six sets of cases for the last bar, where most sets have 15 cases. The oddball set with 19 cases is the one where the obliques for the last bar are already paired up—this you can solve like 5×5 L2C, so there is not anything new to learn. These are the five remaining sets:</p><div class=\"table-wrap\"><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong><img src=\"/stats/tutorial/media/6x6-l2c/en/image10.svg\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><img src=\"/stats/tutorial/media/6x6-l2c/en/image12.svg\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><img src=\"/stats/tutorial/media/6x6-l2c/en/image14.svg\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><img src=\"/stats/tutorial/media/6x6-l2c/en/image16.svg\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><img src=\"/stats/tutorial/media/6x6-l2c/en/image18.svg\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Opposite</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Far Diagonal</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Near Diagonal</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Separate Low</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Separate High</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>12 cases of the \"far\" set are related to some standard commutator. The \"low\" and \"high\" sets are essentially mirrors of each other: if you know an alg for the low set, you can reverse the direction of all the U/F moves to get an alg for the mirrored case (which would necessarily be in the high set).</p><p>Note: these algs are written in SiGN and the spoiler boxes contain more alternative algs than the tables.</p><div class=\"table-wrap\"><table><tbody><tr><td colspan=\"4\"><p><strong>Opposite</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong><img src=\"/stats/tutorial/media/6x6-l2c/en/image20.svg\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><img src=\"/stats/tutorial/media/6x6-l2c/en/image22.svg\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><img src=\"/stats/tutorial/media/6x6-l2c/en/image24.svg\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><img src=\"/stats/tutorial/media/6x6-l2c/en/image26.svg\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><span class=\"tutorial-chip\" data-alg=\"(U) r U 3R U r' U' 3R'\"><strong>(U) r U 3R U r' U' 3R'</strong></span></p></td><td><p><span class=\"tutorial-chip\" data-alg=\"(U') r U' 3R U' r' U 3R'\"><strong>(U') r U' 3R U' r' U 3R'</strong></span></p></td><td><p><span class=\"tutorial-chip\" data-alg=\"(U') r U 3l' U r' U' 3l\"><strong>(U') r U 3l' U r' U' 3l</strong></span></p></td><td><p><span class=\"tutorial-chip\" data-alg=\"(U) r U (l' 3R) U r' U' (l 3R')\"><strong>(U) r U (l' 3R) U r' U' (l 3R')</strong></span></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong><img src=\"/stats/tutorial/media/6x6-l2c/en/image28.svg\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><img src=\"/stats/tutorial/media/6x6-l2c/en/image30.svg\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><img src=\"/stats/tutorial/media/6x6-l2c/en/image32.svg\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></strong></p></td><td></td></tr><tr><td><p><span class=\"tutorial-chip\" data-alg=\"r U r' U 3R U r U' 3r' U r U' r'\"><strong>r U r' U 3R U r U' 3r' U r U' r'</strong></span></p></td><td><p><span class=\"tutorial-chip\" data-alg=\"r U' r' U' 3R U' r U 3r' U' r U r'\"><strong>r U' r' U' 3R U' r U 3r' U' r U r'</strong></span></p></td><td><p><span class=\"tutorial-chip\" data-alg=\"r U r' U2 r U' 3l' U r' U' 3l\"><strong>r U r' U2 r U' 3l' U r' U' 3l</strong></span></p></td><td></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong><img src=\"/stats/tutorial/media/6x6-l2c/en/image34.svg\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><img src=\"/stats/tutorial/media/6x6-l2c/en/image36.svg\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><img src=\"/stats/tutorial/media/6x6-l2c/en/image38.svg\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><img src=\"/stats/tutorial/media/6x6-l2c/en/image40.svg\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></strong></p></td></t